{"title_page": "Amber Mountain rock thrush", "text_new": "{{short description|Subspecies of bird (forest rock thrush)}}\n{{subspeciesbox\n| name = Amber Mountain rock thrush\n| image = Amber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) male 2.jpg\n| image_caption = male, [[Montagne d'Ambre National Park]]\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n| genus = Monticola\n| species = sharpei\n| species_link = Forest rock thrush\n| subspecies = erythronotus\n| authority = ([[Louis Lavauden|Lavauden]], 1929)\n| synonyms = \n''Pseudocossyphus erythronotus''\n}}\n\nThe '''Amber Mountain rock thrush''' (''Monticola sharpei erythronotus'') is a [[songbird]] in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Muscicapidae]], formerly placed in the [[Turdidae]] together with the other [[Chat (bird)|chats]]. It is now usually considered a subspecies of the [[forest rock thrush]].\n\n==Distribution==\nThe Amber Mountain rock thrush is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Madagascar]] where it occurs only on the Amber Mountain massif in the north of the island.<ref name = iucn/>\n\n==Description==\n This is a reeeeeallllly ugly bird. It is kind of sad. ): It makes me feel like I can relate to it and I am sure your ugly ass can too <3. This is a small forest-dwelling thrush, growing to a length of about {{convert|16|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=HBW/> Males have blue hoods, chestnut upperparts, bright orange tail with brown central feathers and orange underparts. Females are mostly brown with an orange wash on the underparts and lack the blue hood. Males are distinguished from other rock-thrushes by the dark rufous back, while the females have bright orange tails and lack white streaking on the breast.<ref name = birdlife>{{cite web | url = http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=31209 | title = Amber Mountain Rock-thrush ''Monticola erythronotus'' | accessdate = 19 Jan 2015 | publisher = [[Birdlife International]]}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode = packed heights = 130px>\nAmber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) male.jpg|male\nAmber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) female.jpg|female\nAmber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) female 2.jpg|female\n</gallery>\n\n==Habitat and ecology==\nIt inhabits mid-altitude and montane humid, evergreen forest from {{convert|800|to|1,300|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and forages inconspicuously in the understorey and on the ground, sometimes sallying to take aerial prey. The species nests in tree hollows or in crevices under overhangs.<ref name = iucn/><ref name=HBW>{{cite web |url=https://www.hbw.com/node/58403  |title=Amber Mountain Rock-thrush (''Monticola erythronotus''). |author=Collar, N. |year=2020 |work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |publisher=Lynx Edicions, Barcelona |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation status==\nThe Amber Mountain rock thrush is listed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]] as Endangered because it has a very small range and its forest habitat is declining in both area and quality. The population is small and believed to be declining, albeit slowly. The total population of this species is estimated to number less than 5,000 individuals, which occur in a single block of forest in the [[Amber Mountain National Park]]. It may be declining, although so far there has been relatively low levels of habitat loss in the area of its occurrence.<ref name = iucn/>\n\n==Taxonomic notes==\nThe Amber Mountain rock thrush has been regarded as a separate species but this view is in doubt. It had been split from the [[forest rock thrush]] because of a variety of morphological differences and in spite of an absence of genetic distinctiveness. As the forest rock thrush and [[Benson's rock thrush]] have been lumped into ''Monticola sharpei'' this taxon has followed suit.<ref name = iucn>{{cite iucn | author = BirdLife International| year = 2016 | title = ''Monticola erythronotus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22730713A95029320 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22730713A95029320.en }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Wikispecies|Monticola sharpei erythronotus}}\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Cruaud |first1=A. |last2=Raherilalao |first2=M. J. |last3=Pasquet |first3=E. |last4=Goodman |first4=S. M. |title=Phylogeography and systematics of the Malagasy rock-thrushes (Muscicapidae, Monticola) |journal=Zoologica Scripta |date=2011 |volume=40 |issue=6 |pages=554\u2013566 |doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2011.00497.x}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2161792}}\n\n[[Category:Birds described in 1929]]\n[[Category:Birds of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Chats (birds)]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Monticola]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Subspecies of bird (forest rock thrush)}}\n{{subspeciesbox\n| name = Amber Mountain rock thrush\n| image = Amber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) male 2.jpg\n| image_caption = male, [[Montagne d'Ambre National Park]]\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n| genus = Monticola\n| species = sharpei\n| species_link = Forest rock thrush\n| subspecies = erythronotus\n| authority = ([[Louis Lavauden|Lavauden]], 1929)\n| synonyms = \n''Pseudocossyphus erythronotus''\n}}\n\nThe '''Amber Mountain rock thrush''' (''Monticola sharpei erythronotus'') is a [[songbird]] in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Muscicapidae]], formerly placed in the [[Turdidae]] together with the other [[Chat (bird)|chats]]. It is now usually considered a subspecies of the [[forest rock thrush]].\n\n==Distribution==\nThe Amber Mountain rock thrush is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Madagascar]] where it occurs only on the Amber Mountain massif in the north of the island.<ref name = iucn/>\n\n==Description==\nThis is a small forest-dwelling thrush, growing to a length of about {{convert|16|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=HBW/> Males have blue hoods, chestnut upperparts, bright orange tail with brown central feathers and orange underparts. Females are mostly brown with an orange wash on the underparts and lack the blue hood. Males are distinguished from other rock-thrushes by the dark rufous back, while the females have bright orange tails and lack white streaking on the breast.<ref name = birdlife>{{cite web | url = http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/speciesfactsheet.php?id=31209 | title = Amber Mountain Rock-thrush ''Monticola erythronotus'' | accessdate = 19 Jan 2015 | publisher = [[Birdlife International]]}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode = packed heights = 130px>\nAmber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) male.jpg|male\nAmber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) female.jpg|female\nAmber mountain rock thrush (Monticola sharpei erythronotus) female 2.jpg|female\n</gallery>\n\n==Habitat and ecology==\nIt inhabits mid-altitude and montane humid, evergreen forest from {{convert|800|to|1,300|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and forages inconspicuously in the understorey and on the ground, sometimes sallying to take aerial prey. The species nests in tree hollows or in crevices under overhangs.<ref name = iucn/><ref name=HBW>{{cite web |url=https://www.hbw.com/node/58403  |title=Amber Mountain Rock-thrush (''Monticola erythronotus''). |author=Collar, N. |year=2020 |work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |publisher=Lynx Edicions, Barcelona |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation status==\nThe Amber Mountain rock thrush is listed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]] as Endangered because it has a very small range and its forest habitat is declining in both area and quality. The population is small and believed to be declining, albeit slowly. The total population of this species is estimated to number less than 5,000 individuals, which occur in a single block of forest in the [[Amber Mountain National Park]]. It may be declining, although so far there has been relatively low levels of habitat loss in the area of its occurrence.<ref name = iucn/>\n\n==Taxonomic notes==\nThe Amber Mountain rock thrush has been regarded as a separate species but this view is in doubt. It had been split from the [[forest rock thrush]] because of a variety of morphological differences and in spite of an absence of genetic distinctiveness. As the forest rock thrush and [[Benson's rock thrush]] have been lumped into ''Monticola sharpei'' this taxon has followed suit.<ref name = iucn>{{cite iucn | author = BirdLife International| year = 2016 | title = ''Monticola erythronotus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22730713A95029320 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22730713A95029320.en }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Wikispecies|Monticola sharpei erythronotus}}\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Cruaud |first1=A. |last2=Raherilalao |first2=M. J. |last3=Pasquet |first3=E. |last4=Goodman |first4=S. M. |title=Phylogeography and systematics of the Malagasy rock-thrushes (Muscicapidae, Monticola) |journal=Zoologica Scripta |date=2011 |volume=40 |issue=6 |pages=554\u2013566 |doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2011.00497.x}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2161792}}\n\n[[Category:Birds described in 1929]]\n[[Category:Birds of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Chats (birds)]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Madagascar]]\n[[Category:Monticola]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fcc8:e848:aa00:e5e3:72b:609f:8cae", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amber_Mountain_rock_thrush"}
