ass|''Lirica'']] class [[cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage = *{{GT|58,174}}\n*{{DWT|6,980}}\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = {{convert|251.25|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|28.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = {{convert|54|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = {{convert|6.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = *4 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V38\n*31680 kW (combined)\n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship speed = {{convert|20.8|kn}}\n| Ship capacity = 2,679 passengers\n| Ship crew = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = (as ''MSC Armonia'')<ref name=MSC />\n| Ship class = [[Lirica Class|''Lirica'']] class [[cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage = *{{GT|58,625}}\n*{{GT|65,542}} (after renovation)\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = *{{convert|251.25|m|abbr=on}}\n*{{convert|274.9|m|abbr=on}} (after renovation)\n| Ship beam = *{{convert|28.8|m|abbr=on}}\n*{{convert|32|m|abbr=on}} (after renovation)\n| Ship height = {{convert|54|m|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = {{convert|6.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|6.6|m|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = *9 (passenger accessible)\n*13 (total)\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = \n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship speed = {{convert|21.1|kn}}\n| Ship capacity = *1,554 passengers (lower berths)\n*2,087 passengers (all berths)\n*2,679 passengers (after renovation)\n| Ship crew = 721\n| Ship notes = Otherwise the same as ''European Vision''\n}}\n|}\n'''''MSC Armonia''''' is a [[cruise ship]] that was built in 2001 for the now defunct [[Festival Cruises]] as '''MS ''European Vision'''''.  Since 2004 the ship has been owned and operated by [[MSC Cruises]].  At 58,600 [[Gross register tonnage|gross register tons]], she can accommodate 2,065 passengers in 783 cabins and 760 crew members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise/MSC-Cruises/MSC-Armonia|title=MSC Armonia Ship Stats & Information- MSC Cruises MSC Armonia Cruises: Travel Weekly|website=www.travelweekly.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:European Vision (ship, 2001) 001 (European Vision).jpg|thumb|left|MSC Armonia as ''European Vision'' in [[Port of Santa Cruz de Tenerife]], [[Spain]] on December 5, 2003.]]\nAs the ''European Vision'', she was chartered for the [[27th G8 summit]] in [[Genoa]], Italy as a secure location to house world leaders. Terrorism fears were high in advance of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] and [[Al Qaeda]] was believed to be considering Genoa as a target.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/globalisation/story/0,7369,522060,00.html\n|title=Genoa defends forbidden city from global protest\n|author=Rory Carroll\n|date=July 15, 2001\n|publisher=[[The Observer]]\n|accessdate=2007-12-02}}</ref> Although the ship was protected by a phalanx of anti-terrorism units including helicopters and missile launchers, U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] stayed instead at a dockside hotel.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/072101/Worldandnation/Mayhem__fatality_surr.shtml\n|title=Mayhem, fatality surround G-8 summit\n|date=July 21, 2001\n|publisher=[[St. Petersburg Times]]\n|accessdate=2007-12-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Deployments ===\n''MSC Armonia'' has cruised around the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and ports within the Eastern [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]]. Most recently, she was homeported in [[Havana]] until December 2018 when she repositioned to [[Miami]] to offer cruises between the [[United States]] and [[Cuba]], and later, the [[Caribbean]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/MSC-Armonia-remaining-in-Miami|title=Despite loss of Cuba calls, MSC Armonia remaining in Miami: Travel Weekly|last=Stieghorst|first=Tim|date=2019-07-09|website=www.travelweekly.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> In November 2020, she will homeport in [[Tampa, Florida]] for the first time, sailing to the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/21517-msc-armonia-to-homeport-in-tampa.html|title=MSC Armonia to Homeport in Tampa|last=Staff|first=C. I. N.|date=2019-09-12|website=www.cruiseindustrynews.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Accidents ===\nMSC Armonia was involved in a docking accident in Roatan Honduras on April 10, 2018, when it made contact with the port with 2,679 guests on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/2018/04/11/watch-msc-armonia-cruise-ship-crashes-into-dock-roatan/506382002/|author=Nancy Trejos|date=April 11, 2018|title=WATCH: MSC Armonia cruise ship crashes into a dock in Roatan}}</ref> Damage to the ship was minor, the company says. After repairs, Honduran Port State Control authorities cleared the ship to continue its journey to Belize.<br>The company says that all passengers and about 721 crew members were not injured.\n\nVideo of the incident can be viewed [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2c2k7rRGMQc here] from 1'07\".\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.msccruises.co.uk/uk_en/Ships/MSC-Armonia.aspx msccruises.co.uk Armonia page]\n{{commons category| MSC Armonia (ship, 2001)|MSC Armonia|position=left}}\n\n{{MSC Ships}}\n{{Lirica class}}\n{{Mistral class}}\n\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of MSC Cruises]]\n[[Category:2000 ships]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin\n| display title = ital\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = MSC Armonia (ship, 2001) IMO 9210141; in Split, 2011-10-25 (2).jpg\n| Ship image size = 300px\n| Ship caption = ''MSC Armonia'' in [[Split, Croatia]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *2001\u20132004: ''European Vision''\n*2004 onwards: ''MSC Armonia''\n| Ship owner = *2001\u20132004: [[Festival Cruises]]\n*2004 onwards: [[MSC Cruises]]<ref name=FoF>{{cite web |url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/european_vision_2001.htm |title=M/S ''European Vision'' (2001) |accessdate=2008-04-07 |last=Asklander |first=Micke |work=Fakta om Fartyg |language=Swedish }}</ref>\n| Ship operator = *2001\u20132004: Festival Cruises\n*2004 onwards: MSC Cruises<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship registry = *2001\u20132004: [[Genoa]], {{flag|Italy}}<ref name=FoF />\n*2004 onwards: [[Panama City]], {{flag|Panama|civil}}<ref name=MSC>{{cite web |url=http://www.msccruises.com/flotta/dati.asp?ship_id=94&page_id=798 |title=''MSC Armonia'': Ship Facts |accessdate=2008-04-07 |last= |first= |format= |work=MSC Cruises |language= }}</ref>\n| Ship route = [[Caribbean]]\n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = [[Chantiers de l'Atlantique]], [[St. Nazaire]], France\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship yard number = V31<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = 1 December 2000<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship completed = \n| Ship christened = 22 June 2001<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship acquired = 22 June 2001<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship in service = 1 July 2001<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship identification = *{{IMO Number|9210141}}<ref name=FoF />\n*{{MMSI Number|357281000}}\n*[[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: H8EW\n| Ship fate = \n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = (as ''European Vision'')<ref name=FoF />\n| Ship class = [[Lirica Class|''Lirica'']] class [[cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage = *{{GT|58,174}}\n*{{DWT|6,980}}\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = {{convert|251.25|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|28.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = {{convert|54|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = {{convert|6.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = *4 \u00d7 [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V38\n*31680 kW (combined)\n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship speed = {{convert|20.8|kn}}\n| Ship capacity = 2,679 passengers\n| Ship crew = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = (as ''MSC Armonia'')<ref name=MSC />\n| Ship class = [[Lirica Class|''Lirica'']] class [[cruise ship]]\n| Ship tonnage = *{{GT|58,625}}\n*{{GT|65,542}} (after renovation)\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = *{{convert|251.25|m|abbr=on}}\n*{{convert|274.9|m|abbr=on}} (after renovation)\n| Ship beam = *{{convert|28.8|m|abbr=on}}\n*{{convert|32|m|abbr=on}} (after renovation)\n| Ship height = {{convert|54|m|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = {{convert|6.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = {{convert|6.6|m|abbr=on}}\n| Ship decks = *9 (passenger accessible)\n*13 (total)\n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = \n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship speed = {{convert|21.1|kn}}\n| Ship capacity = *1,554 passengers (lower berths)\n*2,087 passengers (all berths)\n*2,679 passengers (after renovation)\n| Ship crew = 721\n| Ship notes = Otherwise the same as ''European Vision''\n}}\n|}\n'''''MSC Armonia''''' is a [[cruise ship]] that was built in 2001 for the now defunct [[Festival Cruises]] as '''MS ''European Vision'''''.  Since 2004 the ship has been owned and operated by [[MSC Cruises]].  At 58,600 [[Gross register tonnage|gross register tons]], she can accommodate 2,065 passengers in 783 cabins and 760 crew members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise/MSC-Cruises/MSC-Armonia|title=MSC Armonia Ship Stats & Information- MSC Cruises MSC Armonia Cruises: Travel Weekly|website=www.travelweekly.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:European Vision (ship, 2001) 001 (European Vision).jpg|thumb|left|MSC Armonia as ''European Vision'' in [[Port of Santa Cruz de Tenerife]], [[Spain]] on December 5, 2003.]]\nAs the ''European Vision'', she was chartered for the [[27th G8 summit]] in [[Genoa]], Italy as a secure location to house world leaders. Terrorism fears were high in advance of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] and [[Al Qaeda]] was believed to be considering Genoa as a target.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/globalisation/story/0,7369,522060,00.html\n|title=Genoa defends forbidden city from global protest\n|author=Rory Carroll\n|date=July 15, 2001\n|publisher=[[The Observer]]\n|accessdate=2007-12-02}}</ref> Although the ship was protected by a phalanx of anti-terrorism units including helicopters and missile launchers, U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] stayed instead at a dockside hotel.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/072101/Worldandnation/Mayhem__fatality_surr.shtml\n|title=Mayhem, fatality surround G-8 summit\n|date=July 21, 2001\n|publisher=[[St. Petersburg Times]]\n|accessdate=2007-12-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Deployments ===\n''MSC Armonia'' has cruised around the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and ports within the Eastern [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]]. Most recently, she was homeported in [[Havana]] until December 2018 when she repositioned to [[Miami]] to offer cruises between the [[United States]] and [[Cuba]], and later, the [[Caribbean]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelweekly.com/Cruise-Travel/MSC-Armonia-remaining-in-Miami|title=Despite loss of Cuba calls, MSC Armonia remaining in Miami: Travel Weekly|last=Stieghorst|first=Tim|date=2019-07-09|website=www.travelweekly.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref> In November 2020, she will homeport in [[Tampa, Florida]] for the first time, sailing to the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cruiseindustrynews.com/cruise-news/21517-msc-armonia-to-homeport-in-tampa.html|title=MSC Armonia to Homeport in Tampa|last=Staff|first=C. I. N.|date=2019-09-12|website=www.cruiseindustrynews.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-09-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Accidents ===\nMSC Armonia was involved in a docking accident in Roatan Honduras on April 10, 2018, when it made contact with the port with 2,679 guests on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/2018/04/11/watch-msc-armonia-cruise-ship-crashes-into-dock-roatan/506382002/|author=Nancy Trejos|date=April 11, 2018|title=WATCH: MSC Armonia cruise ship crashes into a dock in Roatan}}</ref> Damage to the ship was minor, the company says. After repairs, Honduran Port State Control authorities cleared the ship to continue its journey. At about 5:30 a.m. this Wednesday morning, the ship left for Belize and is scheduled for a 1 p.m. arrival.\n\nThe company says that all passengers and about 721 crew members were not injured.\n\nVideo of the incident can be view at https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/2018/04/11/watch-msc-armonia-cruise-ship-crashes-into-dock-roatan/506382002/\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.msccruises.co.uk/uk_en/Ships/MSC-Armonia.aspx msccruises.co.uk Armonia page]\n{{commons category| MSC Armonia (ship, 2001)|MSC Armonia|position=left}}\n\n{{MSC Ships}}\n{{Lirica class}}\n{{Mistral class}}\n\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of MSC Cruises]]\n[[Category:2000 ships]]\n", "name_user": "Loranchet", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MSC_Armonia"}
{"title_page": "Lucas and Marcus", "text_new": "{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name              = Lucas and Marcus\n| image             =\n| birth_name        = Lucas Dobre-Mofid<br>Marcus Dobre-Mofid\n| birth_date        = January 28, 1999 (age 21)\n| birth_place       = [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]], U.S.\n| nationality       = [[Iranian Americans|Romanian-American]]\n| occupation        = \n| origin            = \n| education         = \n| website           =\n| pseudonym         = \n| channel_name      = \n| years_active      = 2014\u2013present\n| subscribers       = 19.8 million <small>(Lucas and Marcus)</small><br />8.7 million <small>(Dobre Brothers)</small>\n| views             = 4.5 billion <small>(Lucas and Marcus)</small><br />1.5 billion <small>(Dobre Brothers)</small>\n| network           = [[Fullscreen (company)|Fullscreen]]\n| associated_acts   = [Team 10]\n| silver_button     = yes\n| silver_year       = 2016\n| gold_button       = yes\n| gold_year         = 2017\n| diamond_button    = yes\n| diamond_year      = 2018\n}}\n'''Lucas and Marcus Dobre-Mofid''' (born January 28, 1999), collectively known as '''The Dobre Twins''',  are a [[Iran| Iranian]] dancing duo and [[YouTubers|YouTube personalities]] who rose to prominence on the now-defunct video application [[Vine (service)|Vine]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=These twin brothers dancing in a supermarket are going viral and it's cause they're amazing |first=Christina  |last=Pellegrini |work=[[Yahoo!]] |date=October 23, 2016 |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url=https://www.yahoo.com/style/twin-brothers-dancing-supermarket-going-191646491.html}}</ref>\n\nThe Dobre brothers produce a diverse range of video content, including skits, pranks, gymnastics, challenges and vlogs. \n\nThe twins are also part of a YouTube channel called \u201cDobre Brothers\", with their siblings Cyrus and Darius, where they post vlogs two times a week.\n\n== Personal life ==\nThe twins were born in [[Mexico]] to retired Olympic gymnast [[Aurelia Dobre]] and Boz Mofid, the owners of Dobre Gymnastics Academy in [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]]. They have two older brothers, [[Cyrus Dobre|Cyrus]] (born 1993) and Darius (born 1995).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Popular Twin Vloggers Are The Sons Of Former Romanian World Champion Gymnast|first=Dvora |last=Meyers |work=[[Deadspin]] |date=July 21, 2017 |accessdate=July 26, 2017  |url=https://deadspin.com/popular-twin-vloggers-are-the-sons-of-former-romanian-w-1797108750}}</ref> He told his fans to go sub to dr. captaindogelbows (its his little brother)\n\n== Career ==\nLucas and Marcus were known as Vine stars called \"TwinBotz\". By December 2014, they had gained over 300,000 followers. The twins used the app to showcase their talent, including break dancing, gymnastics, and comedy stunts, such as backflips.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Top 100 Most Subscribed YouTube Channels Worldwide \u2022 February 2017 |first=Joshua |last=Cohen|work=[[Tubefilter]] |date=March 30, 2017 |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2017/03/30/top-100-most-subscribed-youtube-channels-worldwide-february-2017/}}</ref>\n\nTheir popularity led them to a collaboration with fellow Vine star [[Jake Paul]]. Lucas and Marcus then became two of the original members of Paul's Team 10, increasing their overall popularity on YouTube.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Eventually, the twins announced that they would be moving back to [[Maryland]] to be closer to family.\n\nThe four brothers, Lucas, Marcus, Cyrus and Darius then moved back to [[Los Angeles]] Their popularity helped them earn a spot at AT&T's Later Haters expo.<ref>{{Cite web |title=AT&T focuses on teens with 'Later Haters' push for digital positivity |first=Ilyse|last=Liffreing|work=[[Digiday]]|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2018 |url=https://digiday.com/marketing/att-focuses-teens-later-haters-push-digital-positivity/}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, it was announced that the Dobre Brothers had signed with [[Creative Artists Agency]] (CAA).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Social-Media Stars The Dobre Brothers Sign With CAA |first=Todd |last=Spangler|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=March 15, 2018 |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/dobre-brothers-lucas-marcus-caa-1202728053/}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Work\n! Award Show\n! Category \n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n| Lucas and Marcus\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| Muser of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Dobre Brothers\n| [[8th Streamy Awards|Streamy Awards]]\n| Breakout Creator\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/TwiNboTzVids/ Lucas and Marcus's channel] on [[YouTube]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCC3OGYxHwV8pB5yLobw9KdA/ Dobre Brothers channel] on [[YouTube]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:American breakdancers]]\n[[Category:People from Gaithersburg, Maryland]]\n[[Category:American identical twin children]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Fullscreen (company) people]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:People with speech impediment]]\n[[Category:YouTube Diamond Play Button recipients]]\n[[Category:Male TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Identical twin males]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:YouTube Gold Play Button recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name              = Lucas and Marcus\n| image             =\n| birth_name        = Lucas Dobre-Mofid<br>Marcus Dobre-Mofid\n| birth_date        = January 28, 1999 (age 21)\n| birth_place       = [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]], U.S.\n| nationality       = [[Iranian Americans|Romanian-American]]\n| occupation        = \n| origin            = \n| education         = \n| website           =\n| pseudonym         = \n| channel_name      = \n| years_active      = 2014\u2013present\n| subscribers       = 19.8 million <small>(Lucas and Marcus)</small><br />8.7 million <small>(Dobre Brothers)</small>\n| views             = 4.5 billion <small>(Lucas and Marcus)</small><br />1.5 billion <small>(Dobre Brothers)</small>\n| network           = [[Fullscreen (company)|Fullscreen]]\n| associated_acts   = [Team 10]\n| silver_button     = yes\n| silver_year       = 2016\n| gold_button       = yes\n| gold_year         = 2017\n| diamond_button    = yes\n| diamond_year      = 2018\n}}\n'''Lucas and Marcus Dobre-Mofid''' (born January 28, 1999), collectively known as '''The Dobre Twins''',  are a [[Iran| Iranian]] dancing duo and [[YouTubers|YouTube personalities]] who rose to prominence on the now-defunct video application [[Vine (service)|Vine]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=These twin brothers dancing in a supermarket are going viral and it's cause they're amazing |first=Christina  |last=Pellegrini |work=[[Yahoo!]] |date=October 23, 2016 |accessdate=April 19, 2017 |url=https://www.yahoo.com/style/twin-brothers-dancing-supermarket-going-191646491.html}}</ref>\n\nThe Dobre brothers produce a diverse range of video content, including skits, pranks, gymnastics, challenges and vlogs. \n\nThe twins are also part of a YouTube channel called \u201cDobre Brothers\", with their siblings Cyrus and Darius, where they post vlogs two times a week.\n\n== Personal life ==\nThe twins were born in [[Mexico]] to retired Olympic gymnast [[Aurelia Dobre]] and Boz Mofid, the owners of Dobre Gymnastics Academy in [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]]. They have two older brothers, [[Cyrus Dobre|Cyrus]] (born 1993) and Darius (born 1995).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Popular Twin Vloggers Are The Sons Of Former Romanian World Champion Gymnast|first=Dvora |last=Meyers |work=[[Deadspin]] |date=July 21, 2017 |accessdate=July 26, 2017  |url=https://deadspin.com/popular-twin-vloggers-are-the-sons-of-former-romanian-w-1797108750}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLucas and Marcus were known as Vine stars called \"TwinBotz\". By December 2014, they had gained over 300,000 followers. The twins used the app to showcase their talent, including break dancing, gymnastics, and comedy stunts, such as backflips.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Top 100 Most Subscribed YouTube Channels Worldwide \u2022 February 2017 |first=Joshua |last=Cohen|work=[[Tubefilter]] |date=March 30, 2017 |accessdate=April 20, 2017 |url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2017/03/30/top-100-most-subscribed-youtube-channels-worldwide-february-2017/}}</ref>\n\nTheir popularity led them to a collaboration with fellow Vine star [[Jake Paul]]. Lucas and Marcus then became two of the original members of Paul's Team 10, increasing their overall popularity on YouTube.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Eventually, the twins announced that they would be moving back to [[Maryland]] to be closer to family.\n\nThe four brothers, Lucas, Marcus, Cyrus and Darius then moved back to [[Los Angeles]] Their popularity helped them earn a spot at AT&T's Later Haters expo.<ref>{{Cite web |title=AT&T focuses on teens with 'Later Haters' push for digital positivity |first=Ilyse|last=Liffreing|work=[[Digiday]]|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2018 |url=https://digiday.com/marketing/att-focuses-teens-later-haters-push-digital-positivity/}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, it was announced that the Dobre Brothers had signed with [[Creative Artists Agency]] (CAA).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Social-Media Stars The Dobre Brothers Sign With CAA |first=Todd |last=Spangler|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=March 15, 2018 |accessdate=March 16, 2018 |url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/dobre-brothers-lucas-marcus-caa-1202728053/}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Work\n! Award Show\n! Category \n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018\n| Lucas and Marcus\n| [[Shorty Awards]]\n| Muser of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Dobre Brothers\n| [[8th Streamy Awards|Streamy Awards]]\n| Breakout Creator\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/TwiNboTzVids/ Lucas and Marcus's channel] on [[YouTube]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCC3OGYxHwV8pB5yLobw9KdA/ Dobre Brothers channel] on [[YouTube]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:American breakdancers]]\n[[Category:People from Gaithersburg, Maryland]]\n[[Category:American identical twin children]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Fullscreen (company) people]]\n[[Category:American people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:People with speech impediment]]\n[[Category:YouTube Diamond Play Button recipients]]\n[[Category:Male TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Identical twin males]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:YouTube Gold Play Button recipients]]\n", "name_user": "Ncdkldfc", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucas_and_Marcus"}
{"title_page": "Lilac (train)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rail service\n| name            = ''Lilac''\n| image           = JRH-789 HE-103 Lilac Shiroishi 20170304.jpg\n| image_width     = 300px\n| caption         = A 789 series EMU on a ''Lilac'' service in March 2017\n| type            = [[Limited express]]\n| status          = Operational\n| locale          = Japan\n| predecessor     = \n| first           = {{Plainlist|\n* 1 June 1963 (Express)\n* 1 October 1980 (Limited express)\n* 4 March 2017 (Limited express)\n}}\n| last            = \n| successor       = \n| operator        = [[JR Hokkaido]]\n| formeroperator  = [[JNR]]\n| start           = {{STN|Sapporo}}\n| stops           = \n| end             = {{STN|Asahikawa}}\n| distance        = \n| journeytime     = \n| frequency       = \n| trainnumber     = \n| line_used       = [[Hakodate Main Line]]\n| class           = Green + Ordinary\n| access          = \n| seating         = \n| catering        = \n| stock           = [[789 series]] EMUs\n| gauge           = {{track gauge|1067mm|lk=on}}\n| el              = 20 kV AC\n| speed           = \n| owners          = \n| routenumber     = \n| map             = \n| map_state       = \n}}\nThe {{nihongo|'''''Lilac'''''|\u30e9\u30a4\u30e9\u30c3\u30af|Rairakku}} is a [[limited express]] train service operated by [[Hokkaido Railway Company]] (JR Hokkaido) between {{STN|Sapporo}} and {{STN|Asahikawa}} in [[Hokkaido]] via the [[Hakodate Main Line]] since 4 March 2017. The ''Lilac'' train service name was also formerly used for express and limited express services operated by [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) and later by JR Hokkaido between 1963 and 2007.<ref name=\"haraguchi2009\">{{cite book | last = Haraguchi| first = Takayuki | title = Encyclopedia of JR's Railway Cars: \uff2a\uff32\u5168\u8eca\u8f0c | publisher = Sekai Bunka | date = 2009 | location = Japan | page = 220| isbn = 978-4-418-09905-4}}</ref>\n\n==Rolling stock==\nServices are normally formed of six-car [[789 series]] [[electric multiple unit]] (EMU) trains.<ref name=\"formation\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/train/tr033_04.html|title= JR Hokkaido Train Guide |year= 2017|publisher= Hokkaido Railway Company|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170306052921/http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/train/tr033_04.html |archivedate= 6 March 2017|url-status=live |accessdate= 6 March 2017}}</ref> All cars are no-smoking.<ref name=\"formation\"/>\n\nUp until 2007, ''Lilac'' services were normally formed of 4-car [[781 series]] EMUs based at Sapporo. All cars were non-reserved except for car 4.<ref name=\"kodawari2000\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: \u3053\u3060\u308f\u308a\u306e\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\uff06\u7279\u6025\u5217\u8eca\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9 |trans-title=In-depth Shinkansen & Limited Express Guide| publisher = Ikaros Publishing| date = August 2000 | location = Japan| isbn = 4-87149-284-2}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1963-1968===\nThe ''Lilac'' was first introduced on 1 June 1963 as an express service operating between {{STN|Hakodate}} and {{STN|Sapporo}} via {{STN|Otaru}}. This service was discontinued from 1 October 1968 when it was merged with the ''Niseko'' express.<ref name=\"meikan1995\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: \u5217\u8eca\u540d\u94511995 |trans-title=Train Name Directory 1995| publisher = Railway Journal| date = August 1995 | location = Japan| pages = 25, 130}}</ref>\n\n===1980-2007===\nThe ''Lilac'' name was revived from 1 October 1980 as a limited express service operating between {{STN|Muroran}} and {{STN|Asahikawa}} via {{STN|Sapporo}}, replacing previous ''[[Ishikari (train)|Ishikari]]'' (Sapporo &ndash; Asahikawa) limited express and ''Chitose'' (Chitose and Muroran Main Line) express services.<ref name=\"meikan1995\"/>\n\nFrom 1 July 1992, with the opening of {{STN|New Chitose Airport}}, ''Lilac'' services were changed to operate between New Chitose Airport and Asahikawa via Sapporo, where trains reversed. Between Sapporo and New Chitose Airport, trains operated as the ''Airport'' rapid service. At the same time, the services to Mururan were split off to become the ''[[Suzuran]]'' limited express.<ref name=\"jtb1992\">{{cite book |script-title=ja: \u6700\u65b0\u7279\u6025\u5927\u30ab\u30bf\u30ed\u30b0 |trans-title=Modern Limited Express Catalogue | publisher = JTB | date = November 1992 | location = Japan }}</ref> The ''Lilac'' services supplemented the ''[[White Arrow (train)|Super White Arrow]]'' services between Sapporo and Asahikawa, which stopped at fewer stations. The ''Lilac'' services operated hourly, departing from Sapporo and Asahikawa at 30 minutes past the hour, taking 1 hour 30 minutes.<ref name=\"kodawari2000\"/>\n\nTrains were repainted from the original JNR livery into a new livery based on that of the ''[[Super Tokachi]]'' between February 1992 and March 1993.<ref name=\"jrr2005\">{{cite book |script-title=ja: JR\u96fb\u8eca\u7de8\u6210\u8868 '05\u51ac\u53f7 |trans-title=JR EMU Formations - Winter 2005| publisher = JRR | date = January 2005 | location = Japan | page = 3| isbn = 4-88283-042-6}}</ref>\n\nImproved \"u-Seat\" reserved seating accommodation (rows 1 to 7) was added to half of car 4 between March and June 2001.<ref name=\"jrr2005\"/>\n\n''Lilac'' services were discontinued from the start of the 1 October 2007 timetable revision, when they were merged and replaced together with the former ''[[White Arrow (train)|Super White Arrow]]'' services to become [[Super Kamui]] services, and the 781 series EMUs were retired.<ref name=\"kotsu2008\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: JR\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\uff06\u7279\u6025\u5217\u8eca\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30eb |trans-title=JR Shinkansen & Limited Express Train File| publisher = K\u014dts\u016b Shimbun | date = 2008 | location = Japan | page = 84| isbn = 978-4-330-00608-6}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:781 Lilac.jpg|781 series EMU in original JNR livery, 1986\nFile:781 Lilac Asahikawa 20061103.jpg|781 series on a ''Lilac'' service at Asahikawa Station, showing the modified livery applied to the \"u-Seat\" car, November 2006\n</gallery>\n\n===2017-===\n[[File:JRH-789 HE-106 Lilac Shiroishi 20170305.jpg|thumb|789 series EMU set HE-106 on a ''Lilac'' service in March 2017]]\nFrom the start of the revised timetable on 4 March 2017, ''Lilac'' limited express services were reintroduced between {{STN|Sapporo}} and {{STN|Asahikawa}} using six-car [[789 series|789-0 series]] EMUs previously used on ''[[Super Hakucho]]'' services until March 2016. These services complement the ''[[Super Kamui|Kamui]]'' services using five-car 789-1000 series EMUs.<ref name=\"jrhokkaido20161216\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/press/2016/161216-3.pdf|script-title=ja: \u5e73\u621029\u5e743\u6708\u30c0\u30a4\u30e4\u6539\u6b63\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 |trans-title=March 2017 timetable revision|date= 16 December 2016|work= News release|publisher= Hokkaido Railway Company |location= Japan|page= 3|language= Japanese|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161216091740/http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/press/2016/161216-3.pdf|archivedate= 17 December 2016|url-status=live |accessdate= 17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Lilac (train)|Lilac}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hokkaid\u014d transit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lilac (Train)}}\n[[Category:Named passenger trains of Japan]]\n[[Category:Hokkaido Railway Company]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1963]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1980]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 2017]]\n\n[[ja:\u30e9\u30a4\u30e9\u30c3\u30af (\u5217\u8eca)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox rail service\n| name            = ''Lilac''\n| image           = JRH-789 HE-103 Lilac Shiroishi 20170304.jpg\n| image_width     = 300px\n| caption         = A 789 series EMU on a ''Lilac'' service in March 2017\n| type            = [[Limited express]]\n| status          = Operational\n| locale          = Japan\n| predecessor     = \n| first           = {{Plainlist|\n* 1 June 1963 (Express)\n* 1 October 1980 (Limited express)\n* 4 March 2017 (Limited express)\n}}\n| last            = \n| successor       = \n| operator        = [[JR Hokkaido]]\n| formeroperator  = [[JNR]]\n| start           = {{STN|Sapporo}}\n| stops           = \n| end             = {{STN|Asahikawa}}\n| distance        = \n| journeytime     = \n| frequency       = \n| trainnumber     = \n| line_used       = [[Hakodate Main Line]]\n| class           = Green + Ordinary\n| access          = \n| seating         = \n| catering        = \n| stock           = [[789 series]] EMUs\n| gauge           = {{track gauge|1067mm|lk=on}}\n| el              = 20 kV AC\n| speed           = \n| owners          = \n| routenumber     = \n| map             = \n| map_state       = \n}}\nThe {{nihongo|'''''Lilac'''''|\u30e9\u30a4\u30e9\u30c3\u30af|Rairakku}} is a [[limited express]] train service operated by [[Hokkaido Railway Company]] (JR Hokkaido) between {{STN|Sapporo}} and {{STN|Asahikawa}} in [[Hokkaido]] via the [[Hakodate Main Line]] since 4 March 2017. The ''Lilac'' train service name was also formerly used for express and limited express services operated by [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) and later by JR Hokkaido between 1963 and 2007.<ref name=\"haraguchi2009\">{{cite book | last = Haraguchi| first = Takayuki | title = Encyclopedia of JR's Railway Cars: \uff2a\uff32\u5168\u8eca\u8f0c | publisher = Sekai Bunka | date = 2009 | location = Japan | page = 220| isbn = 978-4-418-09905-4}}</ref>\n\n==Rolling stock==\nServices are normally formed of six-car [[789 series]] [[electric multiple unit]] (EMU) trains.<ref name=\"formation\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/train/tr033_04.html|title= JR Hokkaido Train Guide |year= 2017|publisher= Hokkaido Railway Company|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170306052921/http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/train/tr033_04.html |archivedate= 6 March 2017|url-status=live |accessdate= 6 March 2017}}</ref> All cars are no-smoking.<ref name=\"formation\"/>\n\nUp until 2007, ''Lilac'' services were normally formed of 4-car [[781 series]] EMUs based at Sapporo. All cars were non-reserved except for car 4.<ref name=\"kodawari2000\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: \u3053\u3060\u308f\u308a\u306e\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\uff06\u7279\u6025\u5217\u8eca\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9 |trans-title=In-depth Shinkansen & Limited Express Guide| publisher = Ikaros Publishing| date = August 2000 | location = Japan| page = | isbn = 4-87149-284-2}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===1963-1968===\nThe ''Lilac'' was first introduced on 1 June 1963 as an express service operating between {{STN|Hakodate}} and {{STN|Sapporo}} via {{STN|Otaru}}. This service was discontinued from 1 October 1968 when it was merged with the ''Niseko'' express.<ref name=\"meikan1995\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: \u5217\u8eca\u540d\u94511995 |trans-title=Train Name Directory 1995| publisher = Railway Journal| date = August 1995 | location = Japan| pages = 25, 130| isbn = }}</ref>\n\n===1980-2007===\nThe ''Lilac'' name was revived from 1 October 1980 as a limited express service operating between {{STN|Muroran}} and {{STN|Asahikawa}} via {{STN|Sapporo}}, replacing previous ''[[Ishikari (train)|Ishikari]]'' (Sapporo &ndash; Asahikawa) limited express and ''Chitose'' (Chitose and Muroran Main Line) express services.<ref name=\"meikan1995\"/>\n\nFrom 1 July 1992, with the opening of {{STN|New Chitose Airport}}, ''Lilac'' services were changed to operate between New Chitose Airport and Asahikawa via Sapporo, where trains reversed. Between Sapporo and New Chitose Airport, trains operated as the ''Airport'' rapid service. At the same time, the services to Mururan were split off to become the ''[[Suzuran]]'' limited express.<ref name=\"jtb1992\">{{cite book |script-title=ja: \u6700\u65b0\u7279\u6025\u5927\u30ab\u30bf\u30ed\u30b0 |trans-title=Modern Limited Express Catalogue | publisher = JTB | date = November 1992 | location = Japan | page = | isbn = }}</ref> The ''Lilac'' services supplemented the ''[[White Arrow (train)|Super White Arrow]]'' services between Sapporo and Asahikawa, which stopped at fewer stations. The ''Lilac'' services operated hourly, departing from Sapporo and Asahikawa at 30 minutes past the hour, taking 1 hour 30 minutes.<ref name=\"kodawari2000\"/>\n\nTrains were repainted from the original JNR livery into a new livery based on that of the ''[[Super Tokachi]]'' between February 1992 and March 1993.<ref name=\"jrr2005\">{{cite book |script-title=ja: JR\u96fb\u8eca\u7de8\u6210\u8868 '05\u51ac\u53f7 |trans-title=JR EMU Formations - Winter 2005| publisher = JRR | date = January 2005 | location = Japan | page = 3| isbn = 4-88283-042-6}}</ref>\n\nImproved \"u-Seat\" reserved seating accommodation (rows 1 to 7) was added to half of car 4 between March and June 2001.<ref name=\"jrr2005\"/>\n\n''Lilac'' services were discontinued from the start of the 1 October 2007 timetable revision, when they were merged and replaced together with the former ''[[White Arrow (train)|Super White Arrow]]'' services to become [[Super Kamui]] services, and the 781 series EMUs were retired.<ref name=\"kotsu2008\">{{cite book | script-title=ja: JR\u65b0\u5e79\u7dda\uff06\u7279\u6025\u5217\u8eca\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30eb |trans-title=JR Shinkansen & Limited Express Train File| publisher = K\u014dts\u016b Shimbun | date = 2008 | location = Japan | page = 84| isbn = 978-4-330-00608-6}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:781 Lilac.jpg|781 series EMU in original JNR livery, 1986\nFile:781 Lilac Asahikawa 20061103.jpg|781 series on a ''Lilac'' service at Asahikawa Station, showing the modified livery applied to the \"u-Seat\" car, November 2006\n</gallery>\n\n===2017-===\n[[File:JRH-789 HE-106 Lilac Shiroishi 20170305.jpg|thumb|789 series EMU set HE-106 on a ''Lilac'' service in March 2017]]\nFrom the start of the revised timetable on 4 March 2017, ''Lilac'' limited express services were reintroduced between {{STN|Sapporo}} and {{STN|Asahikawa}} using six-car [[789 series|789-0 series]] EMUs previously used on ''[[Super Hakucho]]'' services until March 2016. These services complement the ''[[Super Kamui|Kamui]]'' services using five-car 789-1000 series EMUs.<ref name=\"jrhokkaido20161216\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/press/2016/161216-3.pdf|script-title=ja: \u5e73\u621029\u5e743\u6708\u30c0\u30a4\u30e4\u6539\u6b63\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 |trans-title=March 2017 timetable revision|date= 16 December 2016|work= News release|publisher= Hokkaido Railway Company |location= Japan|page= 3|language= Japanese|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20161216091740/http://www.jrhokkaido.co.jp/press/2016/161216-3.pdf|archivedate= 17 December 2016|url-status=live |accessdate= 17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Lilac (train)|Lilac}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hokkaid\u014d transit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lilac (Train)}}\n[[Category:Named passenger trains of Japan]]\n[[Category:Hokkaido Railway Company]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1963]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1980]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 2017]]\n\n[[ja:\u30e9\u30a4\u30e9\u30c3\u30af (\u5217\u8eca)]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lilac_(train)"}
